<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="280">2.4.4. Adding items</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In this step, the order details are not displayed. They are available again in the third step where you finalise the order. Required adaptations can be made there. <em>But note</em> that addresses, currency and the warehouse cannot be edited in the third step.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>To complete an order, order items have to be added. Execute an <strong>item search</strong> to add items. You can choose between different filters for the item search.<br></p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Item ID</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Item name</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Variation number</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Variation ID</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Additionally, you can activate the options <strong>Only display items in stock</strong> and <strong>Only display sales warehouses</strong>. If you set <strong>a) a warehouse can be assigned for each order</strong> in the basic settings you can only select the option <strong>Only display items in stock</strong> for the search because the warehouse is already determined by the setting. Moreover, the <a href="/en/orders/managing-orders#250">default settings</a> are preselected if you set them.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Click on <strong>Search</strong> (<span class="icon blue"><i class="fa fa-search  "></i></span>) when you have set all the parameters for the search. A table with the corresponding items opens.<br>
This table is customisable. This means that you can decide which information is displayed in the table columns. To do so, proceed as follows.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Customise table:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Configure columns</strong> (<span class="icon "><i class="fa fa-cog  "></i></span>).<br>
→ The window <strong>Configure columns</strong> opens.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select which columns are to be displayed. Take <a href="#table-overview-item-search">Table 4</a> into account.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Move (<span class="icon "><i class="psicon-drag_sort_handle"></i></span>) the columns, so that they are displayed in the order you need them.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Confirm</strong> to save your settings.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>When you set the table once, these settings are saved. The table remains like this even when you finalised this order and are creating a new one. Changes to the layout can be made at any time. A list of the available columns can be found in <a href="#table-overview-item-search">Table 4</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Rows of items with net stock are displayed in white. Rows of items not in stock are displayed in red. For example, if you selected the option <strong>Only display items in stock</strong>, none of the rows are displayed in red at first. Only when stock units go below 0 while adding items to the shopping cart, the row is displayed in red. Thus you can see at first glance in which warehouse items are in stock and can finalise the order faster.</p>
</div>
